<DOC><DOCNO> AP890808-0208 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1327EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-Hewlett-Packard-Samsung     08-08 0183</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Hewlett-Packard-Samsung,0191</SECOND><HEAD>Korea's Samsung to Make Computers Based on H-P Chip Design</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   South Korea's Samsung Electronics Co. Ltd. willmake chips and computers based on technology from Hewlett-PackardCo., the companies said Tuesday.   The alliance will heat up competition in the low-priced segmentof the market for workstations, which are souped-up personalcomputers for scientists, engineers and other power users.   Hewlett-Packard is hoping to use Samsung's manufacturingexpertise to expand sales of computers based on Hewlett-Packard'sdesign for streamlined, speedier computers. The design is known asRISC, for reduced instruction set computing.   Palo Alto, Calif.-based Hewlett-Packard also manufactures itsown computers but focuses on bigger machines with higher profitmargins. The new computers, which will be sold under the Samsungand Hewlett-Packard labels, will be priced to compete withtop-of-the-line personal computers as well as low-end workstationsfrom companies such as Sun Microsystems Inc.   Last month Hewlett-Packard announced a similar deal with HitachiLtd. That one was for bigger, more expensive workstations.   Hewlett-Packard became the world's biggest manufacturer ofworkstations last year when it acquired Apollo Computer Inc.</TEXT></DOC>